missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:21:- The chain mixes true symmetries with bookkeeping conventions. `rescaling` is not a harmless cosmetic move unless the full NS scaling, including time and viscosity normalization, is specified. `conjugate completion` is not cosmetic either; for real-valued velocity fields it changes what the packet literally is. `packet regrouping` can change nonlinear bookkeeping in a way that is mathematically substantive, not merely presentational.
missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:24:- `helical basis choice` is especially slippery here. If the definition is attached to exact mode interactions, basis dependence may reflect a bad representation choice that should be fixed by canonicalization, not a reason to kill the object entirely.
missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:25:- The stable/unstable/conditionally stable table is too coarse. Many workable mathematical objects are only stable after choosing a canonical representation. That is not ideal, but it is not obviously fatal for theorem use.
missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:59:- The final kill condition only flags one kind of circularity: hard-coding Tao's averaged construction back into exact NS language. But circularity can also enter through tuned thresholds, cherry-picked time windows, or choosing a packet representation that predetermines leakage.
missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:70:- The chain overstates the need for representation invariance. For this mission, a theorem object may be perfectly acceptable if it is tied to a canonical Fourier/helical presentation. Full robustness under all regroupings is a luxury standard, not obviously the right one.
