+# Exploration 001 Summary
+
+## Goal
+
+Identify a very small candidate family of exact phase/coherence objects built
+from exact Fourier or helical interaction data, then classify each candidate as
+`intrinsic`,
+`canonically representable but non-intrinsic`,
+or
+`inadmissible`
+under an explicit equivalence and admissibility test.
+
+## What I Tried
+
+- Read the Step-1 mission brief and the winning-chain / intrinsic-audit
+  planning notes first.
+- Pulled the predecessor mission's exact-NS support and canonicalization rules
+  to define the allowed quotient operations honestly.
+- Proposed three candidate classes directly on exact helical/Fourier triad
+  data and screened each one against conjugation, helical-basis conventions,
+  gauge choices, normalization changes, and forbidden desired-channel labels.
+
+## Outcome
+
+`succeeded`
+
+## One Key Takeaway
+
+The best surviving intrinsic object is the coefficient-corrected exact
+triad-phase orbit measure
+`Mu_S(a)`,
+while scalar coherence summaries are only canonical diagnostics and any
+desired-vs-spectator phase split is definitionally inadmissible because it
+imports the target transfer route by hand.
+
+## Leads Worth Pursuing
+
+- Carry the intrinsic object forward as a triad-phase ledger on exact closed
+  supports, not as a one-number score.
+- Let later steps build aggregate diagnostics only after the support and
+  dynamics are frozen.
+- Use the surviving intrinsic object to test whether closure-forced spectator
+  triads destroy phase alignment before any delayed-transfer event can land.
+
+## Unexpected Findings
+
+- The same normalized transfer term that makes a scalar coherence score look
+  natural also explains why the scalar score is not itself intrinsic: the raw
+  orbit data are canonical, but the aggregation is not forced.
+- The predecessor mission's packet-support canonicalization rules are still
+  useful here, but only as equivalence discipline, not as the object being
+  promoted.
+
+## Computations Worth Doing Later
+
+- Derive the exact evolution law for the triad-phase ledger on the smallest
+  recursively closed supports that survive Step 2.
+- Compare the intrinsic triad-phase ledger against any later aggregate
+  coherence score to see whether the scalar summary discards decisive
+  spectator-driven slippage.
